, England"},"nl":{"1395–1470":"1395–1470","1397–Male":"1397–Overleden","1400–Female":"1400–Overleden","1425–1490":"1425–1490","1440–Male":"1440–Overleden","1445–Female":"1445–Overleden","1370–1428":"1370–1428","1370–1449":"1370–1449","29 May 1428":"29 mei 1428","1440":"1440","1395":"1395","Abt 1445":"circa 1445","1470":"1470","1370":"1370","1490":"1490","1425":"1425","1445":"1445","1455":"1455","1400":"1400","Abt 1430":"circa 1430","Abt 1440":"circa 1440","1397":"1397","1428":"1428","1449":"1449","Duckenhalgh, Rishton, Lancashire, England":"Rishton, Lancashire, Engeland, Verenigd Koninkrijk","Rishton, Lancashire, England":"Rishton, Lancashire, England","Rishton Gt. Harwood, Lancashire, England":"Harwood, Lancashire, England","Clayton le Moors, Lancashire, England":"Clayton le Moors, Lancashire, England","Lancashire, England":"Lancashire, England"},"en":{"1395–1470":"1395–1470","1397–Male":"1397–Deceased","1400–Female":"1400–Deceased","1425–1490":"1425–1490","1440–Male":"1440–Deceased","1445–Female":"1445–Deceased","1370–1428":"1370–1428","1370–1449":"1370–1449","29 May 1428":"29 May 1428","1440":"1440","1395":"1395","Abt 1445":"about 1445","1470":"1470","1370":"1370","1490":"1490","1425":"1425","1445":"1445","1455":"1455","1400":"1400","Abt 1430":"about 1430","Abt 1440":"about 1440","1397":"1397","1428":"1428","1449":"1449","Duckenhalgh, Rishton, Lancashire, England":"Rishton, Lancashire, England, United Kingdom","Rishton, Lancashire, England":"Rishton, Lancashire, England","Rishton Gt. Harwood, Lancashire, England":"Harwood, Lancashire, England","Clayton le Moors, Lancashire, England":"Clayton le Moors, Lancashire, England","Lancashire, England":"Lancashire, England","nameMeanings":[{"name":"Rishton","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of Family Names in Britain and Ireland © University of the West of England 2016","meanings":["English:  see  Rushton  . Early bearers: Aleander Rishton, 1560 in   IGI   (Great Harwood, Lancs); Anna Rishton, 1598, Elizabeth Rushton, 1635 in   IGI   (Altham, Lancs); Robert Rishton, 1603, James Rushton, 1627, Robert Riston, 1757 in   IGI   (Colne, Lancs)."],"variants":[{"name":"Rushton","meanings":["English: habitational name from Rishton (Lancashire) and Rushton (Staffordshire), and perhaps also from Rushton (Cheshire, Northamptonshire), Rushton in East Stoke (Dorset), and Rhiston (Shropshire). The placenames derive from Old English <i>risc</i> ‘rush’ + <i>tūn</i> ‘farmstead, estate’."]},{"name":"IGI","meanings":["English: perhaps an altered form of   Pritchett   or   Pritchard  . Compare Katherine Pratchett, 1654, Janam Pritchett, 1675 in   IGI   (Acton by Nantwich, Cheshire); Gulielmus Pritchard, 1675, Mary Pratchett, 1698 in   IGI   (Hatfield, Herts)."]},{"name":"Riston","meanings":["English: habitational name from Long Riston (East Yorkshire), North and South Reston (Lincolnshire), and East and Sco Ruston (Norfolk). The placenames derive from Old English <i>hrīs</i> ‘brushwood’ + <i>tūn</i> ‘farmstead, estate’. The name may sometimes have been confused with   Ritson  .","English: occasional variant of   Rushton  .","Scottish: habitational name from Reston in Coldingham (Berwickshire), cognate with 1 above."]}]},{"name":"Richard","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["One of the most enduringly successful of the Old French personal names introduced into Britain by the Normans. It is of Germanic (Frankish) origin, derived from <i>rīc</i> ‘power’ + <i>hard</i> ‘strong, hardy’. It has enjoyed continuous popularity in England from the Conquest to the present day, influenced by the fact that it was borne by three kings of England, in particular  Richard I  (  1157–99 ). He was king for only ten years (  1189–99 ), most of which he spent in warfare abroad, taking part in the Third Crusade and costing the people of England considerable sums in taxes. Nevertheless, he achieved the status of a folk hero, and was never in England long enough to disappoint popular faith in his goodness and justice. He was also Duke of Aquitaine and Normandy and Count of Anjou, fiefs which he held at a time of maximum English expansion in France. His exploits as a leader of the Third Crusade earned him the nickname ‘Coeur de Lion’ or ‘Lionheart’ and a permanent place in popular imagination, in which he was even more firmly enshrined by  Sir Walter Scott's  novel Ivanhoe (  1820 )."],"variants":[{"name":"Rikert","meanings":["One of the most enduringly successful of the Old French personal names introduced into Britain by the Normans. It is of Germanic (Frankish) origin, derived from <i>rīc</i> ‘power’ + <i>hard</i> ‘strong, hardy’. It has enjoyed continuous popularity in England from the Conquest to the present day, influenced by the fact that it was borne by three kings of England, in particular  Richard I  (  1157–99 ). He was king for only ten years (  1189–99 ), most of which he spent in warfare abroad, taking part in the Third Crusade and costing the people of England considerable sums in taxes. Nevertheless, he achieved the status of a folk hero, and was never in England long enough to disappoint popular faith in his goodness and justice. He was also Duke of Aquitaine and Normandy and Count of Anjou, fiefs which he held at a time of maximum English expansion in France. His exploits as a leader of the Third Crusade earned him the nickname ‘Coeur de Lion’ or ‘Lionheart’ and a permanent place in popular imagination, in which he was even more firmly enshrined by  Sir Walter Scott's  novel Ivanhoe (  1820 )."]},{"name":"Rickert","meanings":["One of the most enduringly successful of the Old French personal names introduced into Britain by the Normans. It is of Germanic (Frankish) origin, derived from <i>rīc</i> ‘power’ + <i>hard</i> ‘strong, hardy’. It has enjoyed continuous popularity in England from the Conquest to the present day, influenced by the fact that it was borne by three kings of England, in particular  Richard I  (  1157–99 ). He was king for only ten years (  1189–99 ), most of which he spent in warfare abroad, taking part in the Third Crusade and costing the people of England considerable sums in taxes. Nevertheless, he achieved the status of a folk hero, and was never in England long enough to disappoint popular faith in his goodness and justice. He was also Duke of Aquitaine and Normandy and Count of Anjou, fiefs which he held at a time of maximum English expansion in France. His exploits as a leader of the Third Crusade earned him the nickname ‘Coeur de Lion’ or ‘Lionheart’ and a permanent place in popular imagination, in which he was even more firmly enshrined by  Sir Walter Scott's  novel Ivanhoe (  1820 )."]}]}],"historicEvents":[{"id":1705197,"age":60,"year":"1455","julianDay":2252488,"title":"Wars of the Roses","description":"Wars of the Roses was a series of English civil wars for control of the throne of England between the royal families House of Lancaster and the House of York. The name of the war was derived as the red rose was the symbol of the Lancastrians and the white rose was the symbol of the Yorks.","url":"https://www.history.com/topics/british-history/wars-of-the-roses","urlTitle":"History - Wars of the Roses","jurisdictionLevel":2}],"lifeSummary":"When Richard Rishton was born in 1395, in Rishton, Lancashire, England, his father, Henry Rishton, was 25 and his mother, Margaret de Legh, was 25. He married Margaret DeHolt about 1430, in Harwood, Lancashire, England. They were the parents of at least 2 sons and 1 daughter. He died in 1470, at the age of 75."},"et":{"1395–1470":"1395–1470","1397–Male":"1397–Surnud","1400–Female":"1400–Surnud","1425–1490":"1425–1490","1440–Male":"1440–Surnud","1445–Female":"1445–Surnud","1370–1428":"1370–1428","1370–1449":"1370–1449","29 May 1428":"29. mai 1428","1440":"1440","1395":"1395","Abt 1445":"umbes 1445","1470":"1470","1370":"1370","1490":"1490","1425":"1425","1445":"1445","1455":"1455"